Histogram Equalization

In histogram equalization, the goal is to create a more uniform distribution of pixel intensities to enhance the contrast of the image

In [3]:
img_arr=np.asarray(grey_img)
img_arr.shape
Out[3]:
(733, 1100)
In [4]:
hist=np.histogram(img_arr)
hist
Out[4]:
(array([     2,     14,   6047,  33105,  47502,  56965,  79188, 181459,
        228718, 173300], dtype=int64),
 array([ 64. ,  81.8,  99.6, 117.4, 135.2, 153. , 170.8, 188.6, 206.4,
        224.2, 242. ]))
In [5]:
flat=img_arr.flatten()
plt.hist(flat,256,[0,256],color='r')
plt.show()
In [6]:
bins=256
histogram = np.zeros(bins)
for pixel in flat:    # loop through pixels and sum up counts of pixels
    histogram[pixel] += 1
hist = histogram
In [7]:
a = iter(hist)
b = [next(a)]
for i in a:
    b.append(b[-1] + i)
cs=np.array(b)
plt.plot(cs)
plt.title("Cumulative sum of the pixel values")
Out[7]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Cumulative sum of the pixel values')

As we can see the values are going above 255, we need to normalize

In [8]:
cs = ((cs - cs.min()) * 255) / (cs.max() - cs.min())
cs = cs.astype('uint8')

plt.plot(cs)
Out[8]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x1f80c799f90>]

Now all the values are within the required range

In [9]:
img_new = cs[flat] #get the value from cumulative sum for every index in flat, and set that as img_new
In [10]:
img_new = np.reshape(img_new, np.asarray(grey_img).shape) #we flattened the image to compute, so now we resize it original image
fig = plt.figure()
fig.set_figheight(5)
fig.set_figwidth(15)

fig.add_subplot(1,2,1)
plt.hist(flat,256,[0,256],color='r')

fig.add_subplot(1,2,2)
plt.hist(img_new.ravel(),256,[0,256],color='r')

plt.show(block=True)

The histogram for a high contrast image(Right) spans the entire dynamic range, but the histogram for a low contrast image(Left) just covers a narrow range.

Translation

it is the shifting of an image along the x- and y-axis. It can shift an image up, down, left, or right, or any combination.

In [12]:
img2=im.open("sun.jpg").convert('L')
plt.imshow(img2,cmap='grey')
img_arr2=np.asarray(img2)
plt.xticks([])
plt.yticks([])
Out[12]:
([], [])

The following code shifts the image 250 units down and 100 units left

In [13]:
tx=250
ty=100
trans_img=np.zeros_like(img_arr2)
r,c=img_arr2.shape
for x in range(r):
    for y in range(c):
        x_new=x+tx #translation
        y_new=y+ty
        if (0<=x_new<r) and (0<=y_new<c): #check if the values are within the range
            trans_img[x_new,y_new]=img_arr2[x,y]
plt.imshow(trans_img,cmap='grey')
plt.xticks([])
plt.yticks([])

([], [])

Rotation

it is a routine that takes an image, a rotation angle, and a point about which rotation is done.

This is the rotation matrix for 2D Images

In [15]:
angle = np.radians(30)  
c_row, c_col = r // 2, c // 2 #centre of the image
rotate_image = np.zeros_like(img_arr2)
for i in range(r):
    for j in range(c):
        y = i - c_row #coordinates with respect to the centre
        x = j - c_col
        new_y = int(x * np.sin(angle) + y * np.cos(angle)) #this is the rotation matrix (multiplied with the x and y coordinates) 
        new_x = int(x * np.cos(angle) - y * np.sin(angle)) #which helps us to rotate the image 
        new_y += c_row #transform back to the original centre
        new_x += c_col
        if 0 <= new_x < c and 0 <= new_y < r: #check if the pixels values are within the range
            rotate_image[i, j] = img_arr2[new_y, new_x]
plt.imshow(rotate_image,cmap='grey')
plt.xticks([])
plt.yticks([])
Out[15]:
([], [])
